tPSPProgressNotes:
Hi Debbie,
 
I realize the April 25 deadline is fast approaching and unfortunately I have not been able to devote much time to this yet,
North Peace Community Resources Society has just had our site visit from Carf in March and The Family Place was part of this process so our accredition with Carf should be here soon (previously the agency was accreditated COA but The Family Place was not part of that process).  
One hurdle at a time: first accreditaion and now FRP standards-  
Question- the information I have read tells acrreditated agencies to focus on B- Do you have any completed templates I can use as a guide so I can get a feel of what it is I need to write to descibe what we do? Unfortunately, I have to work on this alone and wording is difficult for me - I know what we do to meet the standard but struggle with getting it down on paper- not to mention my typing is slow. A completed version would help in that I could revise it to reflect what we do at our Family Place without having to start from scratch.
 
As an accreditated agency-I will be able to use the worksheet to cross reference the policies where policies are required- Do I have to do the A part where policies are not required and it is not part of B template? And if so -what am I supposed to do?
 
Clarification on what is required to submit:
	the worksheet with policies cross-referenced and the document that has our policies 
	B template completed
Thanks, Pam
 
Pam Lillico- Program Co-ordinator
The Family Place 250-785-6021ext. 232
North Peace Community Resources Society www.npcrs.bc.ca
10142 101 Ave. Fort St. John, B.C. V1J 2B3
e-mail: plillico@npcrs.bc.ca  Fax: (250) 785-4659

The Family Centre

The Family Centre is an inclusive family resource centre located
in the Student Family Housing complex supporting a diverse student family community living both on and off campus. Our programsinclude:

clubs for school-aged children, 
information, 
referral and support services,
social events, 
community celebrations, and many more. 

At the Family Centre our goal is to make you feel at home whether
youve come to Uvic from near or far. For more information,
please call us at 250-472-4062 or visit our website at http://
web.uvic.ca/family-centre/

tMembershipNotes:
Submission for Mayne Island's Stream Two Applicati


Dear Debbie,

Allow me to introduce myself-I am Annette Witteman-the new President of the Mayne Island Early Childhood Society-I have been involved as a parent and (part time) Mother Goose Program provider for the past 3 years on Mayne Island and have been a MIECS member since incorporation. I appreciate the complexities and growing pains of a new and young society geographically isolated from both Sault Spring Island and Vancouver. We the new board will need to study how we can make the process as streamlined and effective as possible for the future-we will be holding our first meeting on Sunday and will receive an update from Tina as to how things are ironing out-Also we are working on our charitable status as a society. I look forward to working with you and the BC Association of Family Resource Programs in the future and appreciate your co-operation in clarifying our situation.

Sincerely
Annette Witteman

Site 2 comp 118
490 Fernhill rd
Mayne Island
BC
250-539-5011
annettepmw@shaw.ca

tMembershipNotes:
The name Kla-how-eya is a greeting meaning, Welcome! or how are you? in the Chinook language, commonly used for trading purposes.

Originally called Surrey Aboriginal Cultural Society, Kla-how-eya has become our name to compliment our new Centre. Starting in 1996, SACS has grown to have seven different departments and we are getting closer to our vision for the Community.
